\end{align*}

This new equation indicates that $c + o + n$ equals $t$. Let's call it equation (5):

\begin{align*}
c + o + n &= t \quad \text{(5)}
\end{align*}

We then solve equation (3) for $c$:

\begin{align*}
t + c &= s \\
c &= s - t
\end{align*}

Now we can substitute $s - t$ for $c$ back into equation (5) to find a relationship between $o, n, s,$ and $t$:

\begin{align*}
(s - t) + o + n &= t \\
o + n + s - t &= t \\
o + n + s &= 2t \quad \text{(Add $t$ to both sides.)}
\end{align*}

This leads us to the conclusion that $o + n + s$ is twice the value of $t$. 

From equation (4), we know that $o + n + s$ equals 12. Therefore, we can equate this to $2t$:

\begin{align*}
o + n + s &= 12 \\
2t &= 12
\end{align*}

