\end{align*}

This indicates that the sum of their current ages is $27$.

\begin{align*}
c-4&=a \tag{2}
\end{align*}

Equation $(2)$ stipulates that Chris's age four years ago, which is $c-4$, is equal to what Amy's age is now ($a$).

\begin{align*}
b+3&=\frac{2}{3}(a+3) \tag{3}
\end{align*}

Considering Ben's age in three years ($b+3$), the above equation asserts that it will be $\frac{2}{3}$ of Amy's age at that time ($a+3$).

By expanding Equation $(3)$ and solving for $b$, we get:

\begin{align*}
b&=\frac{2}{3}(a+3)-3 \tag{3.1}
\end{align*}

Now we rewrite $a$ in terms of $c$ using Equation $(2)$ to further simplify our system of equations. So $a=c-4$ and this gets substituted into Equation $(3.1)$ to find $b$ in terms of $c$:

\begin{align*}
b&=\frac{2}{3}((c-4)+3)-3 \tag{3.2}
\end{align*}

Doing the necessary simplification we have:

\begin{align*}
b&=\frac{2}{3}(c-1)-3 \tag{3.3}
\end{align*}

We substitute these expressions for $a$ and $b$ into Equation $(1.1)$. This gives us an equation in $c$ alone:

\begin{align*}
[c-4]+[\frac{2}{3}(c-1)-3]+c&=27 \tag{4}
\end{align*}

Solving this equation allows us to find Chris's current age. Simplify the equation to solve for $c$:

