&= -16(t^2 + 1.5t - 10),
\end{align*}
which simplifies by dividing all terms by $-16$ to give us a quadratic equation in standard form:
\begin{align*}
0 &= t^2 + 1.5t - 10.
\end{align*}
Factoring this quadratic equation, we look for two numbers that multiply to $-10$ and add up to $1.5$. The numbers $2.5$ (positive) and $-4$ (negative) satisfy these conditions, so we can express the factored form as follows:
\begin{align*}
0 &= (t + 4)(t - 2.5).
\end{align*}
This equation is satisfied if $t + 4 = 0$ or $t - 2.5 = 0$. Solving for $t$ gives us the two potential times, $t = -4$ or $t = 2.5$. Because time cannot be negative in this context, the negative value of $t$ is extraneous and does not represent a physical solution to the problem. Therefore, the only valid solution is $t = 2.5$, indicating that the ball will hit the ground after 2.5 seconds.

