Starting with the given quadratic function \begin{align*}
-x^2 -6x +12,
\end{align*}
we factor out a negative one from the terms with $x$ to facilitate completing the square \begin{align*}
-(x^2 + 6x) + 12.
\end{align*}
Next, we find a value to complete the square. This is done by taking half of the coefficient of $x$, which is $6$, squaring it, to get $(6/2)^2 = 9$, and adding and subtracting it inside the parenthesis \begin{align*}
-(x^2 + 6x + 9 - 9) + 12.
\end{align*}
The expression $(x^2 + 6x + 9)$ can be rewritten as $(x+3)^2$ since it is a perfect square, and we then rewrite the expression, extracting $-9$ outside of the parenthesis \begin{align*}
-((x+3)^2 - 9) + 12.
\end{align*}
Simplifying, we have the vertex form of the quadratic function \begin{align*}
-(x+3)^2 + 21,
\end{align*}
where it is evident that $21$ is the maximum value this function can achieve because the square of a real number is always nonnegative, and prefixing it with a negative sign inverts its contribution—making the expression $-(x+3)^2$ nonpositive.

